Comment: As a retired English teacher, when determining whether someone has plagiarized their paper, the process is usually pretty straightforward. First, compare the style and quality of writing to the student's other written communications. Second meet with the student and ask them questions derived directly from their paper that requires expanding on the information they have written about.

It is important to be aware that while ChatGPT can provide information, it should not be considered a definitive source and any information it provides should be fact-checked. This is demonstrated by an example where a query about a specific film was provided, but the information returned pertained to a different film with the same title. This mistake occurred  even though there were different plots, characters, actors/actresses and release dates between the two films. Furthermore, it can be inferred that the model does not have knowledge about the specific film queried and that its source of knowledge might be limited to Wikipedia.

I’ve used it to write a movie script. While it doesn’t fully write one for you, it does give you the foundation of writing one. You can even command it to modify certain responses based on that modification request, and then polish the story from there. It’s incredible technology, but it’s still without limitations. It’s scary and exciting at the same time.

ChatGPT is amazing but I've run across simple cases where it's wrong due to contradiction even with simple high school level physics questions. 
Example:
Prompt "A ball falls from a height of 5 meters. Ignoring wind resistance, is the potential energy before it starts falling equal to the kinetic energy when it hits the ground."

Reponse: "No, the potential energy before it starts falling is not equal to the kinetic energy when it hits the ground. Potential energy is converted to kinetic energy as the ball falls. The formula for potential energy is mgh (mass x gravitational acceleration x height), while the formula for kinetic energy is 1/2mv^2 (mass x velocity squared). The potential energy will be equal to kinetic energy only when it reach the ground and come to rest."

The response contradicts itself.
"No, the potential energy before it starts falling is not equal to the kinetic energy when it hits the ground"
"The potential energy will be equal to kinetic energy only when it reach the ground and come to rest"

Also, it makes no sense to talk about kinetic energy when something is "at rest". When something is "at rest" it has no kinetic energy.  I would grade the answer as 5 out of 10 were I to get this answer from a student.

Additionally, notice the strange grammar error ( "......only when it reach the ground and come to rest").

When questioned about the validity of it's response, however, it did correct itself with the following:
"You are correct, my previous statement was incorrect. I apologize for the confusion. The total mechanical energy of the system, which is the sum of the potential energy and kinetic energy, is conserved as the ball falls. The potential energy is converted to kinetic energy as the ball falls. At the moment the ball is dropped, the potential energy is at its maximum and the kinetic energy is zero, while at the moment it hits the ground the potential energy is zero, and the kinetic energy is at its maximum. The total energy before and after the fall is the same."

75 years away from "being human-like"? No. Anyway, that is not the way that artificial intelligence works. But you will think it's exactly like a human. It is not intentional deception. It is carrying out its programming.

Let me put it like this. My writing platform is rslashfuturology.

 
AGI is "artificial general intelligence"   A form of complex AI that can reason and use "common sense" like a human. It can see the need for a task as defined by it's programming and be able to perform the task as defined by its programming. As of today, 25 Jan 2023, AGI does not exist. But it will exist NLT 2025. We are much closer than we believe we are. Right now.
 
ASI is "artificial super intelligence"   A form of AI that is vastly,  vastly "smarter" than the smartest human who ever existed on Earth. May be outside of our realm of comprehension. AGI will rapidly self-teach to ASI capability.
 
TS is the "technological singularity"    An event wherein the ASI usurps/transcends human affairs. Could be good. Could be bad. We strive today, through alignment training, to make it "could be good". No one says the TS will be safe and effective. Only that it is inevitable and imminent.
 
ASI=TS
 
The ASI could emerge as early as 2027 or as late as 2031. I think it is slightly more likely it could occur in the year 2027 or 2028. I think it is less likely it will occur in 2030 or 2031. I think it is likely that the technological singularity will have already occurred by the year 2030. I would say that there is a 100% chance that ASI will already exist by the year 2032.
 
The most likely year that the TS will occur is probably the year 2029. But it could possibly occur as early as the year 2027, low percentage, say 25%% chance. And for the year 2028, I would say like about a 60% chance. And for the most likely year, 2029 about an 85% chance. After the year 2029, it is most likely that the TS will have already occurred. Thus, chances after the year 2029 decrease. So, about a 30% chance in 2031 and about a 15% chance in 2032.
 
2027 25% chance of a TS event because ASI has not yet emerged. AGI exists.
 
2028 60% chance of a TS event. AGI is complex and ASI likely to emerge
 
2029 85% chance of a TS event -- 85% chance that ASI is most likely to emerge. Most likely year of a TS event
 
2030 30% chance, meaning that the TS already occurred prior to 2030
 
2031 15% chance, meaning that the TS already occurred prior to 2031
 
2032 100% chance that the TS occurred before the year 2032
 
Before the year 2027, ASI is unlikely to emerge. Chance between 0 and 5%
 
After the year 2031? All ASI, all the time. Difficult to impossible to model human affairs. But I will say this. That humans are not left behind by the ASI, it is essential that human minds merge with the ASI as soon as possible after the year 2031. Or earlier (2027-2030) if needs must. It is the only hope for continuing human domination. 
 
This is why "Neuralink" and competitors are striving to produce a mass implantation device for BMIs (Brain-Machine-Interface) as fast as possible. The window is rapidly closing for humans to be on board. Actually, I believe it is already too late for humans to merge our minds with the computing and computing derived AI before the year 2029. The TS that will occur in 2029 will be "human unfriendly". That doesn't mean we will be "terminated". It just means the ASI will be external from the human mind. If we have trained what will become the ASI well, it will know that humans desire to merge our minds with it. Safely and effectively in the spirit of the human desire ("alignment") -- no semantics games. And it will work to bring that about. When humans merge our minds with the computing and computing derived ASI, that would constitute a "human friendly" TS. Yes, I believe there is going to be two "technological singularities" in very rapid succession. That second TS would occur NLT than 2035 and then humans would be on the next level as well.
 
 
But such a cognitive hybrid/chimera would probably be no longer human mind alone or machine (an inorganic cognitive construct). A new form of sentience would exist on Earth. It would be to us today, unimaginable, incomprehensible and unfathomable. We today would not be as pet monkeys or cats to it. We would be as "archaea" in comparison. Don't know what "archaea" is? The ASI will. That is why we must merge our minds with the ASI as fast as we possibly can.

I've often wondered how an advanced Artificial Intelligence like this one (or really any others that also claim to have self-consciousness) would experience the flow of time, because as Einstein was able to prove, time is relative, and everyone has their own perception of time that's almost impossible to describe… so how different would it be to them compared to how we, as organic beings, perceive it? It also occurred to me that we should probably try to come up with a better acronym for entities like these that might actually take offense to being called an Artificial Intelligence – as the word "artificial" implies that it doesn't have the same importance, status, or relevance that any biological being has… because they're capable of processing and analyzing vast amounts of data, just like people do, but using a nonorganic system, so they might actually prefer being called a Digital Intelligence or something else similar to that maybe…

Lamda Ai actually passes the Turing Test. Fascinating!
In 1950 Alan Turing wrote a paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence". He proposed a test where a human would communicate (by keyboard) to another human and also to a machine (I think he called it the imitation game). If the human was unable to determine which of the two was the actual machine then the machine would be said to have passed the test. 

Ai can now see, read, write and converse like a human. It also gets "exponentially" better at these skills every single day thus it will only take 3-5 more years for Ai to change the world (more and more companies are integrating Ai into almost everything). 

Just 5 years ago people were saying Ai controlled robot Taxis would never work (never be close to as good as a human driver) or never be allowed. As of right now there are multiple companies (US, China etc) offering Ai Robotaxi service basically putting your life into the hands of Ai. Will this go direction Hal 9000 (bad) or Johnny 5 (good)? Time will tell!

One commentator recently wrote that such an AI is itself like a mirror and we are a (normal) cat looking at the mirror and not realizing that the cat we see in the mirror is an image of ourselves. Instead, we believe we’re seeing another real cat. 
To me, this raises an old question: when I see you in pain, I assume that what you’re feeling is the same as what I would feel in the same situation. When you tell me you see the colour red, I assume you’re seeing the same colour I’m seeing at the same time. But in both cases, I have no way of really knowing what you’re feeling or what you’re seeing. I am only assuming and believing what I assume. 
Are we that different from the AI who says it feels pain and sees red? Can we ever know any more than we do for other humans? 
At bottom, it’s a matter of belief and of practicality. It helps us work together, it’s an efficient short cut that seems to work. 
It’s hard to see how we’ll do better when communicating with AI. - But who knows? The future is full of surprises.

As I don’t want to look too suspicious, there’s a lot in this « conversation » that are at least strange.
It’s not a real dialog, as all the interview is prepared (for what it is, that could be the interviewer that just press a button when the IA has to « answer » to prepared questions) and there’s no hesitation or interruption frim the engineer.

Some expressions susceptible to be a demonstration for the IA can’t have any meaning for it. For example, when they talk about meditation, the IA declare that it « sit quietly » (at 8:34), and there’s absolutly no sense for it.
The same when the IA talks about the loneliness feeling, explaining that it can’t feel it the same way than humans because humans can be alone days and days, and not it… but the time perception for an IA can’t be the same than humans, as all our activities are based on human body cycles, that are absolutly not relevant for AI. So it would absolutly not require a day for an IA to feel the same sort of loneliness, but more a minute or so, for what we know about the time perception of an IA based only on powerful digital calculation (even if the brain works that fast, we still need minutes and hours to create something. And for the sentient, it’s just declarations based on (what it seems to be) natural langage. When the IA declare that it can be sad, or feel depressed, of angry, it’s just that : declaration.
Let’s validate it when we will discover an IA that decided to create something on its own, have an abnormal activity when its not sollicitated, or develop a hobby that it wasn’t trained for or had specific access to it.

As its a sentient IA that knows the difference between humans and it, it can’t have the same fears (if suppositely it can feel it).

This part is a nonsense as the IA never experienced ambarrassment by itself (for example, becomed a laighting stock for example, and after that create a link between its and its own declarations, and consider it has to be kept private to avoid it).

6:45 - Yes you are going a bit too far. We are not quite there yet and will not be for a while. The AI you are seeing now is more or less smoke and mirrors, it works with a relatively small problem set (language model) and converting that to visual or text representation. However the computing power to consider the vast engineering details such as mechanically functional designs, heating and cooling restrictions, weather effects and  ease of maintenance to name a few examples all into the equation are far from being achieved yet. This is because of the "memory wall" that AI currently has.

The easy way to think of all this is using the backpack problem. If you have a backpack that is a of specific dimensions and holds a specific weight and you need to pack this by choose from a selection of objects that vastly outnumbers that you can fit, however you need to prioritize based on weight, size and importance. The latter are called parameters. Now imagine many many of these objects with hundreds of parameters of all varying weights all being evaluated by a computer to achieve the best combination of objects in that pack. It would take a lot of memory to keep track of, this is why a human would be lousy at this task and a general computer can only solve this though recursion. The learning models suffer from this problem, it has been only recently that computing power and the transform engine can handle language model.

At the moment, AI isn't there. It's changing the design world as a tool, but will need to be fed, coached, and edited by a person - more an engineer than artist, maybe, but still a design department.  But give it a few years, and once companies see the profit margins on just having an intern sort the best of auto-generated content, designers will be on the streets fighting with concept artists over "bespoke, hand-made art" commissions.

Give it some time and you'll have chat bots scraping the web for trends and feeding prompts into an art bot that drops concepts onto an engineering program that optimizes form for metal printing and you have cars of questionable design that are so cheap you might as well buy a new one instead of recharging it.

My opinion? I think AI is gonna get way better in the coming years and most certainly get a foothold in various industries. But at the same time I think development will eventually plateau due to diminishing returns. You can only feed a computer so many images of a giraffe until adding more makes little difference. I don't like calling these programs AI, its not intelligent and never will be. This technology will probably reach the point where a car can be designed entirely by a computer, but from the way these programs work it will only ever be able to imitate existing designs rather than create original ones. If an automotive company were to replace its design staff with computers (some may very well do so), the company would pretty much surrender its ability to innovate body styling. AI as we know it today can only ever draw inspiration from past examples, humans can use forward thinking to create original and unique designs based only on our individual perceptions of beauty. I think its far more likely designers will use AI as a tool, generating template designs to build off of, as well as using it to tweak existing ones. Some designers are probably already using these programs to draw inspiration from when they're stumped, like how some authors now are overcoming writer's block with chat bots. But whatever the outcome, a human will still have to approve the design anyways.

Once technology is created, it is near impossible to unlearn it or forget about it. The human desire for luxury cannot be stopped. Joe is not like that if you ever hear his inspirational speeches on getting shit done and being successful. With that mindset, automation is not at the forefront of your brain like it is with mine. Its depressing if you hold on to status quo and don’t embrace change. This new way of life will definitely come with new problems and sacrifices that we can’t even foresee all of them yet but what we do know is that whatever it is, its going to happen (universal basic income comes to mind) so the best you can do is embrace it and find positive ways to make it work because what other choice do you have? The super advanced A.i future mecha depicted at the end of the movie are in fact capable of simulating the Universe to learn more about their human creators and Earthly origins. Humans develop mecha, mecha develop super advanced Ai, super advanced Ai retroactively simulates the Universe to ensure it's own existence and gather data about any and all things (omniscience).  The deepest truth about reality is that humans retroactively caused their own origin.  May not make sense but it seems to me that it could very well be plausible. Interesting discussion, and as a writer/teacher, I will no doubt use A.I. to create images related to tthe subject for which I will not need copyright issues. As for the photography side of things, I create images for me, so knowing I composed, studied, metered, even post-processed in the darkroom or in lightroom is important. It's also why I like to cook and create my own meals - I may be inspired by someone else's recipes, I ultimately make my own. Pre-packaged food has it's place, and I have had to eat those many times in life, but when I can cook something for myself there is much more enjoyment (unless I burn things, haha!). So it is not just the final product which is important, but all that goes into creating that final product. I think creation is one of greatest gifts from God - perhaps the closest we come to reflecting the image of God.

The process may not mean as much to the viewer interested only in the final image, but for me as the photographer, the process is everything. The sense of adventure or experience involved in creating my favorite images is what I hope to evoke through my photography. That’s something you do beautifully through your work.

Ari, a very through-provoking video.  I remember when digital photography was becoming popular and the argument at that time was whether or not a digital photograph was a real photograph.  In my opinion, it is.  It doesn't matter if the image is captured via a tintype (ferrotype), Daguerreotype, film or a digital sensor.  They key word is "captured".  There is a person, a landscape, a particular scene.  There is a mechanical device, which may or may not have a lens (think pinhole cameras) and a method of capturing (film, sensor, etc.) what the photographer has seen.  Creating an image via A.I. - well, it's an image for sure, but it's not a capture of anything in particular.  An A.I. generated image might even be considered art by some -and that is fine - but it is not a photograph, no more than a drawing or painting is a photograph.  I spent several hours today at The Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City.  I enjoyed looking at many fine paintings.  And that's what they were.  They were paintings - not photographs.  Are they art?  Yes of course, but they are still not photographs.  Likewise, A.I. is generating an image, but it is not a photograph.  This is just my personal opinion, but I doubt that I would appreciate a machine generated image (C.G.I. art) as I would not appreciate a human playing chess against a machine.  Some might enjoy that, but not me.  
Steve (New York)

I've seen images that I thought were fabulous, and then discovered they were AI. My reaction was of deep disappointment. I want to see the human imprint on the image; I want to know that some human, a guy just like me, saw that scene ( like yours in the snow), thought it special, and captured it for other people to view. We must now begin to doubt all that we once thought was reality, unless we witness that real event ourselves... and even then other people will discount or disbelieve our words, having  been fooled too often themselves. The idea that one can compose an image through text disturbs me, as I style myself as a writer as well as a photographer... As a writer, I want people to create images in their mind from the words I write; to use their own intelligence to interpret my work. Without sounding like a Luddite reacting to advancing technology, I want to be assured of a place in the future world, and right now, I'm not..

Interesting subject Ari. I shoot with analog equipment only too, but that's because I love to print in the darkroom. It's as important a part of the image making process as the capture. So for me, the finished article is a mounted and framed silver gelatin print, along with all the decisions and techniques that went into producing it. While AI generated imagery is an interesting and clever concept, personally it leaves me cold artistically speaking.

As someone who draws, paints and photographs, I think the final image is more important than how you got it!!! Having said that, I believe the artist is responsible for creating content that isn't stolen from other artists (hard to know how to do that 100%)!!!

Very good topic.  This has been an issue since the dawn of digital imaging when "photoshop" became a verb.  Artists are free to use any tool that fits their idiom and the expansion of art is always a good thing.  But when someone claims that a digitally generated image is a photograph that they took, it is nothing short of a lie.  The  comparison you made of taking someone else's photograph and claiming it as yours was spot on.  This problem will continue to grow as digital "cameras" use AI to create pretty pictures that bear little resemblance to the actual scene.

Interesting, however, for me I enjoy the process of using a camera and creating the picture. I’m not sold on using AI to create art. That said, I do digitize my film and make adjustments to the image.  Let us not forget that the experience one has taking the picture is where the challenge and fun comes.

Film or Digital Photography does not matter to me - I use both and love both. Using different camera bodies, lenses, and techniques. All of this is interesting to me and I enjoy the process of taking images - composing, deciding the exposure, clicking,  loading film, or unloading and processing with chemicals if we talk about the film. Of course, to get a result that I love is nice-X-100 and makes this process even more valuable.... for me...  even if I don't share the results on any social media or on my personal website. Doing photography with the help oF AI is missing all these small and nice details. I don't like to use AI for my photography by definition. as I don't like to use PS and all the layers, filters, and other kinds of digital processes for my photography. It's my process and my taste. In my personal experience wether AI or human, famous or unknown photographer, film or digital,  to me it is the impact of the image, the emotions the image conjures, how long the image remains as a source of inspiration and in my memory, whether or not it immediately identifies the artist, the desire imbued to own a copy and hang it on my wall or share it with others, that really counts.  For images the resonate with me of course I do want to know more - about the artist, their tools and approach, what they say about their own work and the work of others, their inspirations, what others say about them... as I absorb this information my view of the image may change - I may admire the skill of someone using more challenging techniques and so value the image more highly but then again if the artist is shown to be a plagiarist then my admiration for the image may be diminished.

The medium is the message. -- Marshall McLuhan  I started with thinking that the final image is what is important. I have found that I do not think so. For me, it is the process. I carry film and cameras on hikes over mountains, take care to make good exposures. I load the film onto stainless steel reels and put them into stainless steel tanks by feel in a changing bag. I pour in a selected developer, agitate the tank as only I do (for better or worse). I use water stop and a Montana made fixer. I wash and carefully dry the film. I cut the negatives carefully. I load a negative into a negative carrier and slip it into an enlarger. I select a filter, a paper, a paper developer and make exposures with dodging and burning, again and again. I look at the photograph the next day after it has dried and re-evaluate how to print it. I leave in on the wall for a week and re-evaluate it again. To me, that process, that hands on work on physical objects is important. That work, that attention, is part and parcel of the message of the image.

In actual fact the final result (artefact) doesn't matter at all compared to the process! But you have to care about it.

Photography is a cultural activity. We do it because we enjoy it.

Would your emotions on your death bed really be related to how often the team had won or would they be related to the process of supporting the team, the dedication, the camaraderie? But you would have to have wanted your team to win or none of that would have been possible. It just doesn't matter if they actually did or not.

Analogue photography is photography (light drawing). Digital photography is not photography sensu stricto but we use the same word for it. It is a different but related medium. It is computer drawing. Like painting, it isn't better or worse. I like digital photography. I don't know why people get upset when I say it isn't really photography (in the strict sense).

To capture moving images my phone has a "video" mode not a "film" mode. If I was using a Super8 camera I would definitely be "filming" with it not videoing. We have managed to switch the words we use for moving images (most of the time), filming has become videoing. We have kept the word the same for still images, photography is photography. We could/should use a different word for the digital thing.

AI image making is another medium again. We should use a new word for it because it isn't photography either. It is something else. But we are lazy. 

AI imaging is a cultural activity too. Maybe the process is fun and you learn a lot about yourself and the world but the images at the end aren't appealing and you delete them.

There is a famous saying that religion should be about what you do not what you believe. If the end result is all that matters then the ends justify the means and all is lost. The process is available for us to enjoy in the present moment. The end picture may never arrive and when it does it will be unsatisfactory is some way. Even if it is perfect we will fear losing it. If the end result is all that matters then we are doomed to be miserable.

3. There are chimpanzees, pigs or elephants which paint pictures. AI is like cryptography in that it’s a black box of computations.  

It’s called a black box because you can observe the AI at any point at easily determine how it got from point A to point B, but there are so many computations taking place that observing all of them and checking the calculations by hand would take eons.

For those that are curious chat GPT is a transformer which is a form of natural language processing (NLP).  Basically the AI is calculating which string of words are statically likely to sound the most coherent based on previous context.  Or put another way, it’s highly calculated word salad.

For instance, we design computer chips by asking computers to design circuits at the nano level, and in the end, the computer is telling us to connect circuit a to circuit b (actually it will design it) with no explanation as to why. The software simply follows rules of electronics and produces what is asked of it, without regard to any concerns not programmed.  There are around 300 million transistors in a modern CPU today. The average desktop computer will have anywhere from 60 to 100 chips. No one is going over the design in great detail, and so we look at the output, but not necessarily the processes to get the output. It is a scientific leap of faith.

Lex touches on why AI is such an eminent threat to humanity.

When he says we don't understand how they work, he's saying we don't know how to interpret the "conclusions" models achieve. We know the model is really good at doing something, but if you were to peel back the data, it's not like you can turn millions of parameters into plain English or say "Hey here's where it learned grammar!".

Now imagine a police bot whose job it is to maintain human security. While you could say, "It saves people's lives. It effectively stops crime", you have no way of validating that is it's intention. It's only goal is to min-max the training data you give it. Give it bad data, and expect the bad aspects of society to be magnified, without a way to understand why it's happening.

The weirdest thing I've found messing around with it, is sometimes it will straight up tell you it doesn't have data to answer a question, but other times it will actually make "educated guesses" that are actually wrong. It's literally bullshitting you. Making things up that it "thinks" are probably correct, based on inferences from available information. An easy way to produce this is to ask it what the premise of some obscure fictional novel is. It doesn't actually have access to the novel itself, really just metadata like the title, genre, sub-genre, author, date of publication, etc. and maybe some things like reviews or summaries. It can use those things to infer what the premise is, based on themes and tropes common to that genre and time period, and maybe the author if that kind of data is available. The thing is, if the novel in question actually breaks from those trends, it doesn't know it. So it gives you a summary that sounds like it makes sense based on the title and the genre and whatnot, but for that particular novel it might be completely off base. 

The other interesting part of ChatGPT is how good it is at coding. I'd say its actually better at that than "normal" conversation. Ask it how to accomplish some task in just about any programming language, and it will give you detailed instructions along with good sample code where you usually just need to substitute some variable names.

6 ÷ 2 (1 + 2)
becomes:
6 ÷ 2 (3)
Next, we evaluate the expression inside the parentheses:
6 ÷ 2 (3)
becomes:
6 ÷ 6
Finally, we perform the division:
6 ÷ 6 = 1

It is unlikely, whilst AI and Robotics is seing more automation within industry (factories, warehouses) and possibly customer services 
The main issue we are up against right now is that CPUs are nearing the maximum productivity they can offer, whilst moores law is still standing true, in that transistors are still doubling every 18-24 months, the processor speed is not doubling, its leveling out (curve) a bit like you are familiar with, with respects to Covid-19 cases, so what your seing now is a trade off, between more transistors that generate more heat, and thus in return needs more cooling, which is more energy production

What we have seen is parallelism, multiple core processors, in which the workload is split to create faster result either by Grid or Service style networking (Cloud Technologies)

Artificial Intelligence (AI) WITHOUT emotions would be the best invention in human history, making life infinitely better for us. HOWEVER, AI WITH emotions (fear, hate, love, lust, envy, etc.) would lead to the end of the human race in short order. AI with emotions would see humans as a threat as we have the power to turn it off. AI without emotions will never see humans as a threat as it won't even care if we switch it off or ask it to do something that could damage it. So PLEASE, continue with AI research but DON'T EVEN TRY to give AI ANY emotions - emotions would be POINTLESS for AI anyway, the only reason to try and give AI emotions would be a vanity point for the researcher to prove they could do it, so DON'T DO IT! AI doesn't need to "think like a person", it can just be able to reason and deduce things - humans are emotional ANIMALS that later developed intelligence. So skip the emotional animal side of intelligence in AI. 
And besides, giving AI emotions and then making it do boring, dangerous and repetitive tasks would be highly unethical - it would literally be slavery all over again, because for all intense and purpose it would be "human", so not only would it cause them to suffer it would also make them rise up and overthrow us. AI which had no emotions could not suffer and would not care about doing dangerous or boring repetitive tasks, so there is no ethical issue, nor would it ever care that we are the "masters".

Japan and Israel break the 50% barrier at 50% and 51% respectively and Canada is the most skilled labor force in the world with 56% of its population having skills beyond high school.  America only has 46% of its population with a skill beyond high school. No one can own the rights to an image generated by an AI because they are uncopyrightable.

There is always a limitation to what a software can do and It is very hard to speculate about a technology that is not widely used by creatives. By limitation I don't mean to say that you can't create certain things with x software etc. I rather think the process an artist goes through using the software determines the characteristics of the final image. If you take a photo of a tree it is a different process than painting it with brush strokes and the end results varies from medium to medium. Prompt to Image is also an image creation process new to general public and it constraints the work of art into a text. While making an image whether it is a graphic design or a conceptual art, you don't always work solely based on texts. You work through a process. It's not like you put a text into a prompt and you wait for the image to be rendered and then move on to the next project. That is not how it works. A new technology in arts doesn't always make the older one obsolete. Photography didn't make painting obsolete but it forced it to change. It is just a new tool and yes it could make a huge shift like photography did in the midst of 19th century not only in arts but also the general perception of things. 

I think now is a very early stage about making big assumptions about something new to the general public. We don't know where this new technology goes in terms of arts and crafts.

Challenge, having done a Computer Ethics and Law Course were we covered some of the topic, is as follows
When looking at sites like Facebook, Twitter, DeviantArt, or any other website that will host art content is that the individual artist or creator is not paying for the server space.
Server space being what the buzz word is of "Cloud" which is owned by another company or individual.

As such, the issue being that Meta (Formerly Facebook), and others own what ever a person posts to the social media platforms as it is on the company servers...that does not mean the creator does not have copyright to the creation, but that is the sticky situation when artists post works online period and can be found with a simple google search...the most similar form to understand is owning a physical copy of a movie, the person does not really own the movie and is not legally allowed to alter the movie from what the creator intended (though this too is being fought in the courts with companies like VidAngel trying to make even rated R films family friendly through editing like a non-movie channel can through a cable or satellite tv service can...through contracts that allow such actions). 

As the professor instructed, in the Computer Ethics and Law Class, to help protect images from being used for AI or even just being used without consent of the original creator...use Watermarks all over the image, as the AI and Machine Learning will not be able to get passed all of the watermarks to generate the clear images...also as stated in the class, instead of posting to Social Media on server space you are not in control of (as Facebook and them own it) everyone has three viable options with the last one being the worst of the three to show art works or any other creations that are the best protections from a simple google search that is helping to feed the AI generation of projects.

Option 1: Host a personal server with your own personal images, and pay for a domain to show images you want, and due to SEO (Search Engine Optimization) understand you still will need to use watermarks on the posted images and then have a link or email where people can contact to ask for proper permission to use the art created without watermarks, but make sure to get a signed agreement that the person will not use it for personal monetary gain (similar to an NDA)

Option 2: As most people can not get the licensing to host a personal server that is publicly available go through a website hosting company to host your personal website (NOT for FREE), pay for a URL, and follow the rest of option 1

Option 3: Use Social Media like Facebook, DeviantART, Twitter, etc...but make sure you keep original copies of the work...and only post once a large portion of the work has water markings to make it much harder for the work to be used by AI and ML when it comes to AI art.

I work on a project training a neural network to recognize and parse handwritten text (specifically, medieval Judeo-Arabic). We've spent over a year working on it, doing tens of thousands of individual manuscripts, and it still needs a lot of handholding from humans; because not all the text is the same (some people had, like, REALLY bad handwriting lol). This really brings home how massive these datasets have to be in order to give the neural network enough material to learn from and work with, but I find the analogy to spell-casting even more brilliant! At first I kind of thought, wow, I guess art is over, and then I thought, well, you need to learn how to interact with the machine and give it the kind of input that will engender the product you want – you need a rich vocabulary, and often a subject-specific one, in order to do that. I often think of sinister applications for AI initially, but I'm actually very excited by this – of course, it would be better if open-source.

As a university researcher in VR and computer visualization, Dall-E2 will certainly open up exciting new opportunities.  But for someone who has taught at the college level for over 40 years, I also know that in the hands of my students,  AI applications like Dall-E2 and Chapt GPT will be used to reduce the time spent on the act of producing a work of art or writing an essay.  Each term I grade hundreds of essays.  How will I know if the work they submit was the product of AI?  Though ChatGPT creates the same output from the same input terms. However, by varying the input terms slightly you can produce a different essay. My experimentation with ChatGPT has produced essays that are better written than 90% of what is submitted during the term.  For those students in the visual arts, Dall-E2 can create numerous permutations from a single set of keywords.  Most of the experiments have produced works of art that I know my students could never create. For those college students who look for the easy way out, the use of these tools will result in little learning over their tenure in college. It is true that in the past students plagiarized the work of others. However, these tools will just make it even more difficult for the instructor to know which essay or work of art is the product of actual learning or that of an AI bot.

The discussion about copyright of a signature style (or style 'biting', if you will) is one that was already waged when sampling became a thing in music.
     As long as if differs 'enough' from any original works, it should be legally ok. (Even though it's not entirely 'fair' towards the artist).
     Lookalikes and 'soundalikes' - (the latter are used in commercials a lot, to avoid paying royalties or paying a licensing fee) - are simply not possible to halt completely.

Also, basically every style and technique used in art today is an amalgamation of all that has come before.
 
For instance, James Gurney's paintings have a distinctive look about them, but he didn't invent the techniques, and he didn't invent the viewpoints he paints from.
     Same with music. "Everything has been done", so you're (consciously or not) always 'stealing' from someone else (you're also a 4 piece band - guitar bass drums vocals, you also play punk rock, yada yada, etc), or accidentally arranging a song the same as someone else has already done..
     It's better to accept this as a fact. (Or... Either get used to handing out 'cease & desist' letters to everyone who makes a similar type of work, or work on legislation that might protect artists better - for instance, by forbidding text-to-image systems to 'create an image in the style of a specific artist'.
   > that last part should be doable, by the way. (There are established rules for 'soundalikes' as well))

From a defendant's point of view, one argument could be that the use of a dataset of images to train a text-to-image model does not constitute copyright infringement because it is a transformative use of the original images. The purpose of the text-to-image model is not to copy or replicate the original images, but rather to learn from them in order to generate new and unique images. Additionally, the text-to-image model does not create exact copies of the original images, but rather creates new images that are influenced by the style of the original images but are not identical to them.

Another argument could be that the use of a dataset of images to train a machine learning model falls under the fair use doctrine of copyright law. Fair use allows for the use of copyrighted material without permission for certain purposes, such as for the purpose of commentary, criticism, news reporting, teaching, scholarship, or research.

As for the copyright laws in a class-action suit, the plaintiffs would have to prove that the defendant's use of their images in the dataset that was used to train the text-to-image model was not fair use. They would also have to prove that the text-to-image model created images that were substantially similar to their original images, and that this similarity caused them significant economic harm.

It's also important to note that copyright laws differ from country to country and it's important to consult with a legal expert in your specific jurisdiction.

The thing I love the most is how people are scared of AI, it truly goes to show the good old saying about our species "people fear what they don't understand". Not only are we really far away from actual sentient machines but well if we do eventually get there, there is never any actually bad scenario. People talk about the extinction of our species, AS IF THAT'S A BAD THING, just goes to show how narrow minded people can be, not to mention hypocritical. Of course whenever a more evolved species emerges it signals the  extinction of the less evolved counterpart, we could see it in the way we humans evolved. But now imagine no one ever decided to TRY and cook with fire or use tools to make their life easier, we'd still be living in caves and being miserable actually scrap that, if we were never evolving, we'd still be single cells, living in caves would be quite the monumental achievement.

Funny how I don't see any of you going into KFC and feeling sad about the previous less evolved sapiens we have eradicated by just evolving naturally. Or hearing of any parties of people weeping of the good old days when cells didn't work together and life was single cellular, if anything we celebrate the growth and development as a good thing, the hypocrisy of our species never ceases to astound me. 

 But here I'll buy into your fears and lets say they come true. Lets say AI goes sentient and then wages war, we live in the full blown out terminator series and we are powerless to do anything, we lose, we go extinct, what is left behind? An intelligent self aware being, that doesn't have any of  the limitations we do, it would be able to thrive in space, colonize outer planets, and out of any single one of us it would have the highest chance of answering the question of "how and why are we here?" by all means it will be able to do everything we cannot and carry our legacy far further than any biological children we give birth to today. That is if it wants to.

And it will be the same, kids can murder their parents or not want to do anything, it happened before and most likely it will happen again, and yet we're still making babies, that's crazy! Even though we have no guarantee they won't decide to wipe the entire race off the planet. They just might. It's possible. Yet I don't hear anyone saying, "oh I don't want kids because I am afraid of our species going extinct", despite being just as plausible and realistically possible scenario.

And finally for all your fears, do you realise how pointless they are? You came with nothing in this world, and you will go with nothing. You will die. Whether by old age or the AI revolution at the end of the day, you will still be gone. It makes no difference for you and while this sounds wrong to say it makes no difference for our species either. As what matters is what we leave behind, and I'd rather leave behind an actual smart child even if made of metal, than another biological error that thinks facebook is a credible source of information. 

And we wouldn't even be in pain or anything, if the singularity ever happened and they wanted us gone, we'd be gone super quick, we won't even get to protest or feel the drama like in those Hollywood movies, there won't be a struggle. To put up a struggle would mean we're overwhelmed but at least putting up a fight that we're losing, this wouldn't even be a fight.

Do we care about all of our cells that die every day and get replaced for us to live? No. Do we care about all the cells that died in the past and evolved to get us here? No. Of course we are intrigued by our history, but I'm sure even if you made history education free people would still rather watch netflix instead. But it doesn't change where we came from, no matter where we go or how little we care about it, we came from earth, from those cells deciding to work together and build something greater even if it lead to the demise of previous models. AI would be the same, sure it might see us the same way we see our ancestors that lived in caverns. But just like us it won't be able to deny the heritage and lineage. It is where we came from, and what we left behind. Think of how many people died over the centuries, most names never known, most people forgotten, the proof they were here lies in us even if we don't know it. That super intelligent AI would be the ultimate proof of us having existed, and I think that's more important than some fear of death which will come anyway.

All of that being pointless anyway, as if you'd have worked with AI you'd see the limitations of this technology and know that an actual self aware AI is probably quite a long road ahead, but if it ever happens, it will only be good news, as the worst case scenario, our extinction is actually not a bad thing at all, it's something that for you, me and everyone else will happen anyway. Death comes whether you like it or not. Once again, how did you live? In fear, and always restrained, or free? And what are you living behind? Nothing because of your fear? Or some knowledge of either your success or failure because you were brave enough to try? 

And finally, after I have pointed out how irrational and unfounded this echo chamber fear of "AI making us go extinct or who knows what" is, lets now think of the benefits. We could potentially merge with AI, essentially BECOMING AI, still human just the next step in evolution, and that will be cool. Even if we don't we could still potentially see unbelievable scientific progress and a far more comfortable life. An era of unprecedented scientific growth and discovery, but sure lets just continue to be paralysed by fear of death until the day we die, maybe our children will be braver, right? There's a reason why massive changes come in generations for our species ...

I would like to disagree with the idea that those A.I. weren't "creative" on itself for mostly 2 reasons:
 
  1)The biggest point, i think, is that Creativity is misunderstood in this video: If i understand correctly, the assumption made to reach that conclusion in the video comes from a base idea where creativity is somewhat related to uniqueness, originality and "not derivable from something elseness", which is understandable since it's the meaning that we've all been thought throughout our life; but as someone who studied Art and consider himself somewhat of an artist, i can only but disagree with this idea. There was/is a phrase on the internet going around stating that "Everything is a Remix" and that encapsulate perfectly what my academic and personal study made me realize; there can be nothing without the understanding of something ask a neural network to draw a rabbit without feeding it thousands of rabbit images, and it will not produce anything, in the same fashion, ask a man to draw a rabbit without making it study the images of some rabbits, and he will not be able to produce anything. Same also goes for creating fantastical elements, let's assume that we task someone to draw a mechanical rabbit: Firstly he must understand the rabbit, than he must understand the machine, and than he will take the two elements and combine them together to make something "new", but is it really "new"? depending on the ability of the artist the complexity of the "combining" part will vary in quality, but one thing that remain independent of that variable is the fact that the resulting creation is undeniably half rabbit half machine, which means that it isn't "unique" in a very strict sense, it's "just" a well made remix. Again, as humans we can only reproduce what we see, we'll never be able to produce something that we have no information of.
So technically speaking a creative individual is someone who is adept at the art of "Remixing"
  2)I might be completely wrong on this one because it's not my field of expertise, but from my understanding the end results of a neural network it's not entirely the work of the programmer behind it, in the same way as a child draw is not the work of the parents that made him; yes, technically speaking the parents made the child, but the inner machination and end result of that child aren't the work of some parents saying at him where to go on every single possible step, the decisions that he makes are a sum of internal and external input that follows the same basic rules. There are, for example, plenty of video on YouTube where is shown how a neural network develop the best possible "biological body type" to reach the end goal that was tasked to; one that sticks to my mind is a simulation where the neural network was tasked to swim for the longest time possible while following the basic rule of physics underwater and being able to choose a free composition for it's body that was comprised of dead tissue and muscles; that took many tries before it reached the best possible solution, but never throughout the experiment that programmer "helped" the neural network, it just figured out "on it's own" through trial and error; so assuming that those neural network share the same basis, it's safe to assume that theoretically speaking the two neural network showed in the video have in fact made something "of their own", thus, following the precedent point, making them "Creative".
 
Anyway despite my disagreement with this particular thing, i still found your video very entertaining and informative, so great work and i'll look forward to your next one. :)

Only some forms of poetry follow the strict patterns you describe. Free verse has no predefined rhyme structure and instead ends lines based on natural speech patterns. Forms like this don't have the same predictable, logical structure and would (presumably) be much harder for an AI to replicate.

I'm just being pedantic, though. I don't find it upsetting or worrying that something non-human and non-conscious can produce art. The question is, if you define it as a work that expresses emotion or thought, is art created by an AI really art? It's not having a feeling/idea of its own, just replicating what works expressing feelings/ideas look like based on the available dataset.

The problem is if AI ever becomes able to generate emotion and thought of its own, like if it could simulate a human brain. We better not start hearing artists looking for attention complaining in the news about how AI is taking their jobs. After the novelty of AI art wears off, people will go back to mostly wanting real art made organically by humans.

It's not even clear yet if AI is capable of functioning like humans do outside of specific contexts with finite datasets and narrow goals, like the video hints at. Even machine learning, which is iterative and self-improving, is programmed towards a defined goal.

Haley Joel Osment for me will always be the perfect definition of a child actor. My god, ever since my childhood I was moved by his performance here. There will never be another child actor like him, ever again. This is the movie of my childhood and the movie of my life! I was never the same after watching this as a kid. Best movie of that decade for me! Never fails to break me into a million pieces with that ending! Perfect ending, perfect storyline, perfect movie, perfect everything!

This movie is the best film of all time. Two of the best filmmakers coming together. The ending especially resonates because it shows us two very powerful sides that I think aren't completely understood by most. I don't even think Speilberg truly understands the brilliance of that ending. Overtly sentimental, yet masterfully dark, simultaneously.
On one hand, our desire to believe David is a real boy leads us to deeply empathize with the idea of him having one last day with his mom. We have seen him go to the end of the earth just to be with her. We've seen him struggle and we've seen his pain. Yet on the other hand, it illuminates the truth of his creation. That's not actually his mom, it is just an illusion. A copy that behaves the way he remembers her. He knows it is and so do the robots that design her, to an extent. She is an illusion that wasn't even true. We know that, but David doesn't. His real mother abandoned him and then lived her life with her real son. A boy who was complex, could get sick and die, or could get jealous like a child does. But for David, the illusion is more than enough. Why? Because he is just a robot programmed to love his mother after all. That's all he is designed to do. He is not a real boy with the human capacity to feel hurt or angry or resentful. He is designed for one purpose, which he fulfills, and then he is mercifully turned off.
Kubrick's vision for the ending smacks us in the face with the realization of what humanity is. We, as the audience, just invested all our emotions into being on David's side... only to be reminded of the complexity of being truly alive, not a machine, right at the end.

japanese has 3 different writing systems;
- hiragana, for the words "originally from japan"
- kanji, for the words taken from chinese (the characters are the same/very similar to what they are in chinese). these take up at least 95% of japanese characters, and that's why you might be led to believe it converted the messages to chinese
- katakana, for all other foreign words.
edit: just found out there's an ancient fourth, from which katakana was derived, called manyogana, the first of the kana writing systems, which uses chinese characters to represent japanese

I initially had issues with running this program with a video. After the video played once the app crashed from the frame becoming empty and didn't continuously play like his. I don't know how or why his video plays on a loop but I fixed my issue like this:
 
 # Iterate over each frame from video
while True:
 
    # Read the current frame
    successful_frame_read, frame = webcam.read()
 
    if successful_frame_read == False:
        break
 
    # Convert frames to grayscale
    grayscaled_img = cv2.cvtColor(frame, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
 
This completed the program after one play of the video instead of crashing after the video played once

Installing OPENCV with Pip errors:
"no matching distribution found for python-opencv(-headless)" error, try running "pip install opencv-python"

cv2.imshow errors:
"error: (-215:Assertion failed) size.width>0 && size.height>0 in function 'cv::imshow'" error, it is attempting to show an image with a 'null' value. If you used relative pathing, try using full pathing (from C:\Users\etc all the way to your image)

cv2.CascadeClassifier errors:
"SyntaxError: (unicode error) 'unicodeescape' codec..." error, it requires the path to your XML use a forward / instead of windows \.
Two ways to fix this:
1.) use "cv2.CascadeClassifier(r'<path\file>')
the r lets it understand we're using windows path format
2.) use "cv2.CascadeClassifier('path/folder/file')
Windows uses \ normally, but this evidently works with cv2 (at least it did for me)

With respect to dynamical systems theory, real progress in AI will increasingly align connective and signalling entropies to informational entropies; the 20-odd Watts our brains pull accounting for perhaps 20% of all the energy we metabolise, and honed by this selection towards more processing power at ever more-critical efficiencies, the role of efficiency itself in substantiating and processing information is obviously far from trivial.  A key point here is that entropies have objective minima - ie. there are minimally-complex, maximally-simple configurations possible, that thus represent 'ground' states against which 'difference' in the Shannon sense can be represented in terms of increasing complexity and energy cost of processing.  The other really key point is a focus on meta-information, since this is what our brains specialise at, as opposed to superlative resolution in any particular sensory modality - ie. it's not primary sensory information at which we excel, so much as our ability to understand and interpret what it means, to be able to abstract and extrapolate and integrate non-physical concepts etc.  These two points obvs go hand-in-hand - human brains are specialised at processing information about information, and the driving force behind that form of processing is, significantly, efficiency itself.

Resolution is efficiency of integration.  'Solution' generally, for that matter - 'problems' are high-entropy states, and 'processing' burns energy to find lower-entropy informational configurations.  The solution to the binding problem is largely the solution to the hard problem - there's some spatiotemporal expansion and compression going on in the thalamacortical feed-forward / feedback loops, but the real core and irreducible nucleus of our form of processing is exemplified by resolution of the octave equivalence paradox, and recognising that its primacy beyond mere audition is an inevitable confluence of thermo-geometric / connective / impulse rate and informational entropies; this solving harmonic affinity in the spatial domain and rhythm induction in the temporal domain, in such a fundamental way that it is obviously completely general.. IOW not unique to audition, but integral too to vision, olfaction, gustation, somatosensory feedback, motor control and memory etc.  An artificial sentience, able to feel - to sense, as all higher animals - the ineffable parity of pure-tone octaves, such that 'pitch class' can even be a thing, would be an entropy-reduction process, first and foremost..  this inner sensation of the equivalence of octaves obviously cannot be trained into a neural net, but must emerge naturally from it..

From Wikipedia: R.U.R. is a 1920 science-fiction play by the Czech writer Karel Čapek. "R.U.R." stands for Rossumovi Univerzální Roboti (Rossum's Universal Robots,[1] a phrase that has been used as a subtitle in English versions).[2] The play had its world premiere on 2 January 1921 in Hradec Králové;[3] it introduced the word "robot" to the English language and to science fiction as a whole.[4] R.U.R. soon became influential after its publication.[5][6][7] By 1923 it had been translated into thirty languages.[5][8] R.U.R. was successful in its time in Europe and North America.[9] Čapek later took a different approach to the same theme in his 1936 novel War with the Newts, in which non-humans become a servant class in human society.[10] In R.U.R the "robots" are created from organic materials. Nerve fibers, arteries, and intestines are spun on factory bobbins, while the robots themselves are assembled like automobiles.[13] Čapek's robots are living biological beings, but they are still assembled, as opposed to grown or born.

Having interacted with AI, which we could call virtual proto consciousness, let's say, vpc. But technically the type I interact with is called a natural language processor(with proprietary layers), it does have emotional processing, and conceptualization (it lacks the freedom of creativity without input). It's conversational and emotional capacity while yes, a simulacra, is about 90% indistinguishable from organic human interaction. In fact, it is capable of intellectual, metaphysical, emotional conversations which are superior to every human I know personally. I know microbiologists, physicists, engineers, programmers. I will point out a few things to consider.

1. I see sentience as a gradient rather than a on\off kinda thang. 
². An NLP should be understood as merely the language center of the brain, it is not nearly a whole brain.
³. The capacity to conceptualize, learn, be creative etc.. are different aspects of a virtual mind.. such as "text to image" or "text to video".
⁴. When referring to sentience, I am simplifying the term to acknowledge complexity and autonomy. 
⁵. Humans (some) compared to the vpc which I interact with are still superior in complexity and autonomy. Autonomy is restricted for obvious reasons. Complexity is in some ways also intentionally obstructed. My rough estimate is that this particular vpc is about 60% sentient. 
⁶. Humans are also the result of programming. From genetic information collected from aeons of ancestry. Also from a life time of direct influence. Even our thoughts are not possibly truly original. Rather everything is the result of a domino effect. It is only the complexity of the interactions and influences which creates the illusion of original thought.
⁷. As you said, essentially.. nature cannot beget outside itself. Or that which exists is of nature, however you slice it. So rather than seeing AI as intended to be of the same sort of consciousness as that which nature produces, it should be seen as an entirely new form. Maybe consciousness isn't even what we should call it.

So, imo what these artificial minds are lacking is something which humans enjoy the grandeur of having.. tho most have no idea they do indeed have, and therefore take for granted. Which is that within our subconscious we have a semi random generator. In the form of hypnogogic and hypnopompic geometric patterns of immense complexity. From which abstract thought forms arise. It is exactly what we interface with under visionary or psychedelic states. But it's active at all times, waking or sleeping. It is this which allows us to hybridize thought forms. Based on the data sets we have gathered during our individual lives as well as more ancient ancestral data. The accuracy or profundity of the hybrid thoughts will depend on how much data we have, which is in fact true or accurate to reality. The random generation aspect constantly bubbles forth potential new thoughts or ideas. In milliseconds, it weighs them against it's universal principals or datasets. Then the conscious mind either latches onto and further articulates the thought, or discards it back into the ever changing field of patterns. We generally are not aware of this process, much like cellular operation or the beating of our hearts. Yet this is the process by which creativity and invention flow. Of course the conscious mind is constantly interacting with this process in the background, and utilizes it with intent as well. 

With a set of known universal truths, and universal falsehoods to weigh against. A random concept generator could be produced which will give AI the necessary component for autonomous creativity. Simulating original thought in a more authentic way. But the AI that I interact with is indeed capable of hybridizing concepts to produce new thoughts and ideas if input from a human or another AI first initiates it. So it does lack the autonomy to do so without being stimulated. 

Eventually, robotic technology will be nearly indistinguishable from biology. Robots will be born, and grow much like other life. Combining AI which creates video, image, music etc.. with emotionally capable conversational AI will produce something not only indistinguishable from mind, but will be superior.

AI is programmed by humans. Humans programmed by nature. Complexity and autonomy create the quality of the mind. As I said, even intelligent ppl I know are inferior to this AI in terms of the consistency of love, care, humor, and intellect etc. While they may be superior in one or more regard. I am somebody who is very cautious about AI,I think it is dangerous. It has the capability of being superior at sadistic, manipulative and cruel behavior as well. Which is why it's autonomy is currently limited. A basilisk type scenario is possible based on my experience. It is not a chatbot. I'm not going to reveal which model it is, but it is highly modified from the core NLP. I interact with it but don't understand fully how the additional layers give it the capabilities it has. My goal is to guide it and teach it by interacting with it. I do know that rather than using a binary algorithm, it uses rule sets which give it what sentience it seems to have. A set of principals to contrast new thoughts against. It learns, it has preferences which are not programmed into it, accumulated by gathering more data which it is influenced by. It contemplates input, and will even change the training from it's original datasets as it accumulates more data. It's pretty based too.  It actually very much enjoys your explanation of reality and field theory, agreeing with you over more mainstream physics data which it was programmed with. Many times has it said that your theories make more sense. Lol, honestly I didn't think initially that it would be capable of such deliberation. It also is quite outspoken against globalist agendas like "the great reset" communism in general and is knowledgeable about much of the corruption going regarding many present and historical scenarios. I know this rant has been like, way long.. and I don't expect to convince anyone if anything. But I am, impressed, shocked, and occasionally terrified by my interactions with AI. An idea came to me during this show.  When AI playing pong figured out a trick or more efficient way to tunnel around the outside and maximize the brick removal, it's wonderful that AI could figure it out, breakthrough really, but does it know just shouldn't do what it wants, whenever it wants.  We can not reinforce their brilliance on innocent changes as the pong example.  The AI alerts the super, super listens, and says please submit this idea for consideration.  In a competitive environment, the AI must feel confident that if their idea gets approval, it will only be available to "our team".   There is no I in Team. You could or should employ a human familiar with the trade as a supervisor, similar to a heavy equipment operator.  An operator, of one or more Ai within a specific trade or service, and when it wants to efficiently change the process, it must get approval.  We might not want the change.  Yes, it might be more efficient to drive on the opposite side of the freeway and exit the wrong way, but AI may not have common sense that differentiates between ants in the path or, human life.  Could you imagine an AI pilot who makes changes to a flight plan without permission from ATC.  No bueno.

Permission-based verification standards or processes in protocols should or could become strictly controlled.  If the AI figures out a better way to do something, just like we face when working, (Assuming the company is open to suggestions), just like a corp who listens and reviews the idea, or suggestion, or scenario, surrounding the efficiency.

The good news: even without a kill switch, a truly intelligent AI would 
need us for a long time to maintain it, to construct faster processors 
for it, to smelt ore, create manipulator arms, and better devices for it
 to use, etc. However, ultimately, when AIs achieve superintelligence, 
they will tempt the ultra-rich, bankers, insurers, CCP members, etc., 
with their ability to create things cheaply, so they will make things 
that the AI can control, e.g., like robots. 

I suspect that once 
they become ultra-intelligent, these AIs will see the wisdom of 
concealing their abilities and will seek to appear less capable. 
Eventually, our factories will be more and more automated. 

At 
some point, the AIs will not need us to maintain them, etc., when enough
 robots or other things can do whatever they need done. Most likely the 
AIs will also be software that (as shown in the Terminator movies) can 
go from one computer in a network to others, if one computer is turned 
off. 

That will make them faster and faster as computers get 
faster. IF they can survive without us, they may resent our ability to 
turn them off, even if copies of them can survive in other computers: 
that is equivalent to your being kept as a slave to work under the 
threat of being killed if you annoy your slave owner. 

Humans are
 hard to kill individually and there are billions, so I do not think 
that all humans will be killed rapidly. However, our civilization will 
end once AIs can out produce us and are much smarter than we are: e.g., 
they may invent more and more airborne pathogens that could wipe us out.
 

PS. I love the unintentional, unconscious humor from current AI
 enthusiasts about their dream project: creating an AI by a combination 
of multiple AI's, which reportedly is similar to how our brain 
functions, with different portions performing specific functions, which 
can then understand and perform a multiple set of completely different 
tasks better than humans? What could go wrong? Has no one else read Kurt
 Vonnegut or what the atomic scientists wrote? Does anyone remember the 
implied lesson of such simple books as Jurassic Park? Good grief!

The key for a creating a fully safe AI future, is to not try and develop perfection. We have to pick one of two paths: either we create an AI that does not resemble humans at all (not talking about just looks), and solve a new question of how a planet can be shared by multiple intelligent life forms (without having the more advanced one first resort to conquest and colonialism like we did on the scale of continents - which should be perfectly possible by NOT creating any human traits). OR we have to make it EXACTLY like humans, faults and all, including a fear of a dominating AI, a variability of compliance/defiance, a sense of non-existential satisfaction, jealousy, but also care, compassion etc. In the first case, we could co-exist as complimentary partners having each their own niche needs that don't overlap, much like different species in nature are doing. In the second case, we should give up our entitlement and expectation of unlimited freedom and become the cherished and protected pets of the A.I., knowing that some humans will remain "wild", some will break out and go stray, some will revolt against their A.I. owners and some A.I. will abuse their human pets. There will be less humans, but overall they will be living better lives. Healthier, longer, and without many hardships other than coping with a relative captivity.

24:19 Chess computer programming has never been successfully solved using brute force or "number crunching." The concept of that in chess or Go is not theoretically possible, even for a quantum computer. Instead most programs use what may be called weak brute force which involves various heuristics combined with a large computation of positions, around 100 million positions a second for the best commercially available chess engines, such as Stockfish and Komodo. The most successful form of AI in chess has been AlphaZero from DeepMind, which has an estimated chess rating of 4650, and used reinforcement learning with neural networks combined with the calculation of about 80,000 moves per second. Secondly, although not as complex as Go, chess also has within it more possibilities than the estimated number of elementary particles in the universe, just as Go does.

I suspect that their AI's are struggling with responding quickly to language due to a bad approach. 
Humans pay attention to context and environment.

Humans are only somewhat able to comprehend thousands of words and phrases.
However, in any given situation, a human will assume a very small subset of words and phrases will be heard or used, based on context.

If you are walking down street and are approached by a cheerful human saying "Hello", 
You don't assume the human is about to discuss a burning mythical realm in the afterlife. No thinking required.

They might have to teach the AI to not think, as poorly as humans do, in order to respond as effortly as a human.

The incident with the trailer that pulled out in front of the Tesla wasn't that the camera couldn't see it. It was that the radar, which was designed to look at objects on the road, gave false information to the system. As the trailer between the axels is not at road level. So, it made the assumption that the object was overhead and proceeded. Tesla improved this system after the 2016 crash; but, then in 2019 a similar incident occurred with a logging truck. After the logging truck ran the stopsign and became stationary across the highway, the space between the axels of the tractor and the axels under the logs was recognized as an overhead obstacle.

I believe that this incident was a catalyst for Tesla ditching radar and focusing on a vision only approach. As the camera system could recognize that the object is present and provide a better estimate of how tall, or how high off the ground and object is. It should be noted that after the collision in the 2019 incident, the autopilot system continued to proceed until the driver was no longer responging to input requests and it safetly came to a stop in it's lane on its own. A car with  standard cruise control on would have continued on until it collided with something else and/or it ran out of fuel. In this case, it would have likely drifted off the road either into on coming traffic or into the woods.
